<BaseLayout
	title='What I Teach — Guitar, Bass &amp; Ukulele Lessons | Jonathan Zalzman'
	description='Rock, blues, funk, jazz, fusion, prog, shred, metal, theory, ear training, bass, ukulele, songwriting, improvisation. The full breakdown of what you can study with Jonathan Zalzman in Suwanee, GA.'
	nav='teach'
>
<!-- ===================== PAGE HERO ===================== -->
<section class="page-hero">
  <div class="page-hero-inner">
    <div class="crumbs">
      <a href="/">Home</a>
      <span class="sep">/</span>
      <span>What I Teach</span>
    </div>
    <div class="page-num"><span class="ix">02</span> What I Teach</div>
    <h1>Bring Your <em>Sound.</em><br>I'll Help You <span class="accent">Find It.</span></h1>
    <p class="page-lede">Beginner to advanced, six-year-old to sixty-year-old, classic rock to modern prog. <b>Here's the full menu</b> — pick one, pick a few, or come in unsure and we'll figure it out together.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ===================== INTRO ===================== -->
<section class="page-section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="teach-intro">
      <div>
        <div class="section-eyebrow" style="color:var(--ember-deep)"><span class="num" style="background:var(--ember-deep);color:var(--bone)">★</span> The Approach</div>
        <h2>One Teacher. Nine Styles.<br>One Plan Per Student.</h2>
        <p>I don't pick the curriculum off a shelf. I teach what you want to learn, in the order that makes sense for where you are now. Below are the styles I'm most fluent in — but the goal isn't to cover all nine. It's to figure out which two or three are <i>your</i> path, and go deep.</p>
        <p>If a style you love isn't on this list, ask anyway. I'll tell you straight if I'm the right fit or recommend someone who is.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="iso-num">9</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ===================== STYLES LIST ===================== -->
<section class="page-section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <article class="style-detail">
      <div class="sd-num">01</div>
      <div class="sd-title">
        <h3>Rock &amp; Blues</h3>
        <div class="sd-tags"><span>Beginner — Advanced</span><span>Most Popular Starting Point</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="sd-body">
        <h4>// What It Is</h4>
        <p>The bedrock of the electric guitar. Open chords, power chords, riffs, blues bends, the pentatonic scale, twelve-bar form, classic-rock vocabulary that sets you up for almost everything else.</p>
        <h4>// Who It's For</h4>
        <p>New students who want to play <b>actual songs</b> in their first month. Adult comeback players. Anyone who lights up to Hendrix, Zeppelin, AC/DC, SRV, Black Keys, Jack White.</p>
        <h4>// What We Cover</h4>
        <ul><li>Open chords and power chord shapes</li><li>Strumming patterns and rhythm grooves</li><li>Pentatonic scale and basic improvisation</li><li>Bending, vibrato, slides — the expressive moves</li><li>Reading riffs, tabs, and basic charts</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
<article class="style-detail">
      <div class="sd-num">02</div>
      <div class="sd-title">
        <h3>Funk &amp; Groove</h3>
        <div class="sd-tags"><span>All Levels</span><span>Rhythm-First</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="sd-body">
        <h4>// What It Is</h4>
        <p>The most underrated thing on the guitar — making people move. Sixteenth-note feel, ghost notes, tight muting, chord voicings that breathe, pocket awareness. This is the stuff most rock players never learn, and it changes everything.</p>
        <h4>// Who It's For</h4>
        <p>Players who already know some chords but feel like their <i>strumming sounds stiff</i>. Anyone who loves Vulfpeck, James Brown, Prince, Cory Wong, Daft Punk-era funk, or modern jam-funk.</p>
        <h4>// What We Cover</h4>
        <ul><li>Sixteenth-note rhythm vocabulary</li><li>Ghost notes and percussive muting</li><li>Triad inversions and seventh-chord voicings</li><li>Single-note funk lines and double-stops</li><li>Locking in with a drummer (or click)</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
<article class="style-detail">
      <div class="sd-num">03</div>
      <div class="sd-title">
        <h3>Jazz &amp; Fusion</h3>
        <div class="sd-tags"><span>Intermediate — Advanced</span><span>Theory-Heavy</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="sd-body">
        <h4>// What It Is</h4>
        <p>Chord-melody, walking bass on guitar, improvising over changes, modal playing. Plus the fusion side — the ECM/Holdsworth/Scofield/Metheny world where jazz vocabulary meets rock energy.</p>
        <h4>// Who It's For</h4>
        <p>Players ready to dig into theory. Adult students who always wanted to "understand" music. Advanced students who want to leave the pentatonic box and play <i>over the chords, not at them</i>.</p>
        <h4>// What We Cover</h4>
        <ul><li>Major/minor 7th and extended chord voicings</li><li>ii-V-I progressions and how to navigate them</li><li>Modes (Dorian, Mixolydian, Lydian and friends)</li><li>Targeting chord tones in solos</li><li>Comping behind a soloist</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
<article class="style-detail">
      <div class="sd-num">04</div>
      <div class="sd-title">
        <h3>Progressive &amp; Shred</h3>
        <div class="sd-tags"><span>Intermediate — Advanced</span><span>Technique-Forward</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="sd-body">
        <h4>// What It Is</h4>
        <p>The technique to play fast, accurately, and musically. Alternate picking, economy picking, sweep arpeggios, two-hand tapping, string skipping, odd time signatures, polyrhythms.</p>
        <h4>// Who It's For</h4>
        <p>The student who has heard Plini or Polyphia or Animals as Leaders or older Steve Vai/Satriani and thought <i>I want to be able to do that</i>. Teens chasing modern prog. Adults rebuilding lost speed.</p>
        <h4>// What We Cover</h4>
        <ul><li>Alternate picking economy and accuracy</li><li>Sweep picking arpeggios (3-string, 5-string, 6-string)</li><li>Tapping (one-finger, multi-finger, two-handed)</li><li>String skipping and wide intervallic patterns</li><li>Counting and feeling odd time (5, 7, 9, mixed)</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
<article class="style-detail">
      <div class="sd-num">05</div>
      <div class="sd-title">
        <h3>Metal</h3>
        <div class="sd-tags"><span>All Levels</span><span>Aggressive Technique</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="sd-body">
        <h4>// What It Is</h4>
        <p>Tight rhythm playing, gallop picking, palm muting, drop tunings, chuggy riff-writing, lead techniques borrowed from prog. Old-school to new-school — Metallica through Periphery and beyond.</p>
        <h4>// Who It's For</h4>
        <p>Teens who already love the genre and want their playing to actually <i>sound</i> like it. Adults reconnecting with the music they grew up on. Anyone who wants the right hand to be a weapon.</p>
        <h4>// What We Cover</h4>
        <ul><li>Palm muting and the gallop</li><li>Drop tunings (D, C#, B, drop A) and how to navigate them</li><li>Riff writing — the architecture of a heavy song</li><li>Pinch harmonics, dive bombs, and the "voice" of metal</li><li>Soloing over riff-based contexts</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
<article class="style-detail">
      <div class="sd-num">06</div>
      <div class="sd-title">
        <h3>Theory &amp; Ear Training</h3>
        <div class="sd-tags"><span>All Levels</span><span>The "Why" Behind Everything</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="sd-body">
        <h4>// What It Is</h4>
        <p>How music actually works — and how to <i>hear</i> it. Intervals, scales, chord construction, key signatures, functional harmony, transcription. The kind of knowledge that lets you learn songs by ear and write your own.</p>
        <h4>// Who It's For</h4>
        <p>Anyone who feels like they're learning songs but not learning <b>music</b>. Players who want to write or compose. Students who want to read sheet music or charts. Adults who never had formal training and feel a gap.</p>
        <h4>// What We Cover</h4>
        <ul><li>Intervals — the building blocks of melody and harmony</li><li>Major and minor scales, modes, and how they relate</li><li>Chord construction (triads, sevenths, extensions)</li><li>Functional harmony (what chords <i>do</i>, not just what they're called)</li><li>Transcribing solos and songs by ear</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
<article class="style-detail">
      <div class="sd-num">07</div>
      <div class="sd-title">
        <h3>Bass &amp; Ukulele</h3>
        <div class="sd-tags"><span>All Ages</span><span>Different Instruments, Same Standards</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="sd-body">
        <h4>// What It Is</h4>
        <p>Not a guitar player? Same studio, same approach. Bass groove fundamentals, slap technique, walking bass lines. Ukulele chords, strumming, fingerpicking — great for kids, comeback adults, and travelers.</p>
        <h4>// Who It's For</h4>
        <p>Bass-curious players who want to anchor a band. Parents looking for a less intimidating starter for their child than guitar. Songwriters who want a portable, friendly instrument.</p>
        <h4>// What We Cover</h4>
        <ul><li>Bass: pocket fundamentals, root-fifth-octave, scales, slap basics</li><li>Bass: reading tab and bass clef, locking in with drums</li><li>Uke: open chords, strumming patterns, common keys</li><li>Uke: fingerpicking, basic chord-melody</li><li>Both: building a song repertoire from day one</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
<article class="style-detail">
      <div class="sd-num">08</div>
      <div class="sd-title">
        <h3>Songwriting &amp; Composition</h3>
        <div class="sd-tags"><span>All Levels</span><span>Bring Your Ideas</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="sd-body">
        <h4>// What It Is</h4>
        <p>Turning sparks into actual songs. Form, voice leading, arrangement, dynamics, lyric prosody, demo recording. We don't just <i>learn</i> songs — we make them.</p>
        <h4>// Who It's For</h4>
        <p>Players who have ideas (or full song fragments) and don't know how to finish them. Anyone wanting to release original music. Students who want to use the guitar as a <b>writing</b> tool, not just a performance one.</p>
        <h4>// What We Cover</h4>
        <ul><li>Song form (verse / chorus / bridge — and when to break it)</li><li>Chord progressions that don't bore you</li><li>Arrangement — knowing when to add vs. subtract</li><li>Lyrics, melody, and how they should fit together</li><li>Demo recording basics (DAW, mics, scratch tracks)</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
<article class="style-detail">
      <div class="sd-num">09</div>
      <div class="sd-title">
        <h3>Improvisation</h3>
        <div class="sd-tags"><span>Intermediate</span><span>The Jam-Band Mindset</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="sd-body">
        <h4>// What It Is</h4>
        <p>Soloing as a conversation, not a recital. How to listen to the band, take risks, build tension and release, follow an idea through changes. The jam-band approach — but applicable to any genre.</p>
        <h4>// Who It's For</h4>
        <p>Players who can solo a little but feel like every solo sounds the same. Anyone who wants to <i>jam</i> — sit in, play with friends, take a real solo at an open mic. Cover-band players who want their leads to feel alive.</p>
        <h4>// What We Cover</h4>
        <ul><li>Listening — the most important improvising skill</li><li>Theme and variation: developing a single idea</li><li>Tension and release across a solo arc</li><li>Trading fours and call-and-response</li><li>Soloing over modal vamps vs. changing chords</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>

    <div class="inline-cta" style="margin-top:60px">
      <div>
        <h3>Don't See Your Thing? Just Ask.</h3>
        <p>This list isn't exhaustive — it's the styles I get the most students for. If you have a specific player or song in mind, mention it when you book. The first lesson is free either way.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/lessons#book" class="btn btn-primary" style="white-space:nowrap">Book a Free Trial <span class="arrow">→</span></a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
</BaseLayout>
